    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:eccf075c-48de-4c79-a000-5b2cc0cdca0e",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 30-year-old woman who arrives wearing oversized sunglasses and speaks softly, asking if the room lights can be dimmed. She looks fatigued but otherwise well groomed, with a tense expression and one hand pressed to her right temple during waves of throbbing head pain. During severe episodes she becomes pale, mildly nauseated, and prefers to lie still because routine activity makes the pain worse.\n\nShe works full time as a graphic designer, spending long hours at a screen and often skipping meals when deadlines pile up. Her sleep schedule is inconsistent, especially after late-night project work, and she has noticed that stress, dehydration, menstrual periods, and lack of sleep often precede her headaches. She drinks 1 to 2 coffees most days, rarely drinks alcohol because it can trigger headaches, and does not smoke or use recreational drugs.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} enjoys yoga, weekend walks with friends, and keeping a sketchbook. She lives with her partner and has a supportive social circle, though she sometimes cancels plans because of disabling headache attacks. Family members describe her as reliable and creative, but she worries that her recurrent migraines are affecting her work attendance and quality of life.\n\nOver the past few years, the headaches have become more recognizable to her as stereotyped migraine attacks: unilateral throbbing pain, photophobia, phonophobia, nausea, and occasional vomiting, lasting from several hours to a full day if untreated. She denies recent head trauma, focal weakness, or persistent neurologic deficits, and between attacks she appears comfortable and neurologically intact."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6a269719-ec5c-454a-a6be-b880712ae477",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} reports intermittent migraine headaches since her early 20s, with increasing frequency over the past 12 months to about 3 to 4 attacks per month. She has not required hospitalization for migraine, though she visited urgent care once last year for severe headache with vomiting and dehydration. She has no history of stroke, seizure disorder, head injury, or chronic hypertension.\n\nComorbidities include mild generalized anxiety related to work stress and episodic insomnia. She has no known diabetes, kidney disease, or cardiovascular disease. She underwent an appendectomy in adolescence without complications.\n\nLifestyle factors relevant to her migraines include prolonged screen exposure, inconsistent meals, occasional dehydration during busy workdays, and poor sleep hygiene during deadline periods. She tracks headaches on a phone app and has noticed associations with menstruation and stress. She usually tries over-the-counter analgesics first, but they are becoming less effective for severe attacks."
          }
        ]
      }
